President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate Tanya J. Bradsher for the position of Deputy Secretary of Veterans Affairs. Bradsher currently serves as the Chief of Staff at the United States Department of Veterans Affairs and has a background in the military, having served for 20 years in the United States Army. She has also held various roles in the Obama-Biden and Biden-Harris Administrations, including serving on the White House's National Security Council and as Assistant Secretary for Public Affairs at the Department of Homeland Security. Bradsher holds an M.A. in Strategic Communications from George Washington University and a B.A. from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

Additionally, President Biden has nominated Margaret L. Taylor for the position of Legal Adviser of the Department of State. Taylor is currently the General Counsel of the United States Agency for International Development and has previously held positions at the Brookings Institution, Lawfare, and the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. She has also worked as an attorney at the U.S. Department of State, where she advised on various legal aspects of foreign assistance programs and international law enforcement matters. Taylor holds an A.B. from Princeton University and a J.D. from Columbia Law School, where she served as the Editor-in-Chief of the Columbia Law Review.

These nominations are part of President Biden's efforts to fill key leadership positions in his administration.